#Approach:

Isomorphic Strings – HashMap Mapping Approach

Is problem me hume check karna hota hai ki string s ke har character ko
string t ke kisi character se consistently replace kiya ja sakta hai ya nahi.

Sabse pehle dono strings ki length compare karte hain.
Agar length different ho, to wo isomorphic ho hi nahi sakti.

Phir hum ek HashMap use karte hain
jisme s ka character key hota hai aur t ka corresponding character value hota hai.

String ko character by character traverse karte hain:
Agar current character of s pehle map me nahi hai,
to check karte hain ki t ka current character kisi aur key ke saath already mapped to nahi hai.
Agar mapped hai, to do alag characters same character par map ho rahe hain, jo allowed nahi hai,
to false return kar dete hain.

Agar current s character already map me present hai,
to check karte hain ki wo same t character ko hi map kar raha ho.
Agar nahi, to mapping inconsistent hai, so false return kar dete hain.

Agar poori string traverse ho jaye aur koi issue na aaye,
to strings isomorphic hain.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1) / O(n)

#Code:

class Solution {
    public boolean isIsomorphic(String s, String t) {

        //check if they are equal in length or not 
        if(s.length() != t.length()){
            return false;
        }

        HashMap<Character, Character> map = new HashMap<>();

        for(int i=0; i<s.length(); i++){
            char orignal = s.charAt(i);
            char replacement = t.charAt(i);

            if(!map.containsKey(orignal)){
                if(!map.containsValue(replacement)){
                    map.put(orignal, replacement);
                }
                else{
                    return false;
                }
            }
            else{
                char check = map.get(orignal);
                if(check != replacement){
                    return false;
                }
            }
        }
        return true;
        
    }
}
